{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e8fbcf4-6c33-4c6b-b626-552f437f5752","content":"Update these three files:\n\n**1. `*.csproj`**\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\n**2. `global.json`**\n```json\n{ \"sdk\": { \"version\": \"11.0.100\" } }\n```\n\n**3. `Dockerfile`**\n```dockerfile\nFROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspnet:11.0 AS base\nFROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:11.0 AS build\n```\n\n**Then:**\n- Install the .NET 11 SDK locally (`dotnet --version` to confirm).\n- Run `dotnet restore` to update dependencies.\n- Check for any NuGet packages targeting `net10.0` — update those to versions supporting `net11.0`.\n- Run `dotnet build && dotnet test` to verify everything compiles and passes.\n\nReview the [.NET 11 migration guide](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/compatibility/11.0) for any breaking changes that may affect your app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c836c1ff-b569-4c63-b646-3141d74a891f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about updating from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any files since they described their setup. Let me provide concise guidance.\n\n.NET 11 would follow the same pattern as previous .NET upgrades. As of my knowledge cutoff (early 2025), .NET 11 hasn't been released yet, but the pattern is consistent across versions.","outputTokens":372,"requestId":"CFE2:164D4D:1998224:1CFF94B:69E821FC"},"id":"0ac222b7-313e-4d17-a23e-606fd67c4b84","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:19:00.340Z","parentId":"c4289247-ff94-4b10-a462-fc6508bb14d4"}
